Head (
Fig. 22
): semicircular, as long as width (HW/HL = 1.19 , n = 20 ), widest at posterior part of eyes; setae on vertex rather dense but inconspicuous, directed anteriomedially; punctation medium in size, evenly scattered rather densely; vertex longitudinally lack of punctation at middle, but small to medium in size. Eyes: medium in length, occupying approximately half length of head, slightly protruding laterally.

Antennae (
Fig. 40
): short, moderately shorter than head and pronotum combined; thick, setose, with antennomere IV moderately transverse, but antennomeres V to X strongly transverse in approximately same width each; antennomere XI symmetrical, obtusely rounded at apex; approximate relative length of antennomeres from basal to apex: 19 (including base): 8.5 : 9 : 4 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 5 : 13 .

Pronotum (
Fig. 4
): transversely oval (PW/PL = 1.41 , n = 20 ), strongly narrowing anterad, moderately longer than sutural length of elytra, widest around below of basal half, basal margin weakly rounded; pubescence dense, directed laterally and posterolaterally; covered uniformly and densely with small, shallow punctation.

Mesoventrite (
Fig. 31
): inter coxal process rather narrowly elongate, with rounded apex, completely reaching to inter coxal process of metaventrite.

Elytra (
Fig. 4
): together, transverse (EW/EL = 1.93 , n = 20 ), rather small, slightly smaller than pronotum, widest at middle; fine pubescence scattered densely, diverging posteriorly on each elytron; dorsal surface rough and impressed finely and shallowly; posterolateral corners of each elytron not sinuate.

Legs (
Fig. 4
): simple, short, moderately slender; fore and midtibia, densely covered with undeveloped spines, respectively.

Abdomen (
Fig. 4
): first three visible tergites deeply impressed transversely at base; dorsal and ventral surface moderately covered with long thin setae.

Male : tergite VIII (
Fig. 72
): posterior margin smooth, not serrate at all, weakly but clearly emarginate broadly and medially; dorsal surface covered with setae rather densely, with approximately 9 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 74
): posterior margin broadly rounded, with a row of sparse minute sensory setae (see
Yamamoto & Maruyama, 2012
: 10 ), and with a complex-cluster of very minute setae just behind the row of minute setae; ventral surface densely covered with setae, with approximately 11 macrosetae. Median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 76–77
): [lateral view (
Fig. 76
)]: robust, gradually narrowing apically; apical lobe sharply pointed, not hook- shaped at apex; [parameral view (
Fig. 77
)]: bulbous, with basal part widely rounded; apical lobe abruptly narrowing moderately near apex, with narrowly and acutely pointed apex; a series of complex sclerites, not reaching to beyond basal 1 / 3 of median lobe.

Female : tergite VIII (
Fig. 73
): posterior margin as in male; dorsal surface covered densely with setae, with approximately 10 macrosetae. Sternite VIII (
Fig. 75
): posterior margin very weakly rounded broadly or almost truncate; ventral surface covered with setae rather densely, with approximately 12 macrosetae. Spermatheca (
Fig. 78
): C-shaped; apical invagination of spermatheca deep and conical in shape; spermathecal head and neck forming elliptical shape together; attachment of spermathecal duct inconspicuous; basal part of spermathecal stem almost straight, as long as spermathecal head and neck combined; chitinized portion of spermathecal stem moderately long, almost same as length of spermathecal head and neck combined; each part of spermatheca uniformly and weakly sclerotized; inner wall of spermathecal head and neck rather densely striate, that of basal part not reticulate at all.

Distribution. Japan [Hokkaidô, Honshû, Shikoku, Kyûshû; Okushiri-tô Is., Oshima-ôshima Is., Izu-ôshima Is., Shikine-jima Is., Miyake-jima Is., Mikura-jima Is., Hachijô-jima Is., Chichi-jima Is., Haha-jima Is., Minamiiôjima Is., Shôdo-shima Is., Okino-shima Is. (
Kôchi
), Okino-shima Is. (Fukuoka), Tsu-shima Is., Yaku-shima Is., Amami-ôshima Is., Okinawa-hontô Is., Tokashiki-jima Is., Aka-jima Is.]; Korea , China .

Comments. This
Aleochara
species is commonly found throughout the entire Japanese territory, including small islands, spanning the northern part (Hokkaidô) to the southwestern part of Japan (Okinawa-hontô Island) (see
Fig. 124
). Records of
A. parens
from China and Korea are also known (
Cho & Ahn, 2001
;
Luo & Zhao, 2012
).
